==English==
===Etymology===
A possible phonological mutation introduced by way of Ancient Greek transcription of [[Ancient Egyptian]] ''[[pr-aa]]'' (''per-aa''), "the Great House", from ''[[pr]]'' meaning "dwelling-place", "temple" or "house" + the suffix ''[[-aa]]'' designating "great", "spectacular" or "excellor".

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# The supreme ruler of [[Ancient Egypt]]; a formal address for the sovereign seat of power as personified by the 'king' in an institutional role of Horus son of Osiris
# A personification of Ancient Egypt, i.e. a metonym for Ancient Egyptian sovereignty, much like ''[[White House]]'' may refer to America's presidency, ''[[Kreml]]'' to the Russian presidency, or ''[[Westminster]]'' to British political systems.

